I completely understand what you want to achieve. You want to build a system where a user can browse or use AI (RAG - Retrieval-Augmented Generation) to search through your 15+ pre-designed floor plans. Once the user finds a layout they like, the system fetches that specific JSON from the database, loads it into the canvas, and allows them to adjust the walls and customize it to their exact requirements.

The great news is that your existing 2D engine is already fully equipped to handle this. Your FloorPlanner class has an importState(jsonStr) method that perfectly reconstructs a project from JSON, and once loaded, all walls, furniture, and anchors are fully interactive and editable!

Here is the architectural plan and the code on how you can implement this RAG + Template Loading feature.

Step 1: Database Schema for the Projects
In your database (e.g., MongoDB, PostgreSQL, or Firebase), you need a table/collection for your templates. To make RAG work well, you must include a text description of the layout.

json
{
  "_id": "project_01",
  "name": "Modern 2BHK with Open Kitchen",
  "description": "A 1200 sqft modern home featuring 2 bedrooms, an open kitchen, a spacious living room, and a front balcony.",
  "json_data": "{ ... your exported FloorPlanner JSON string ... }",
  "thumbnail_url": "https://your-storage.com/thumb_01.jpg"
}
Step 2: The RAG / Search Backend (Node.js Example)
If you want users to "chat" or search for a design using natural language (e.g., "Show me a house with a large balcony"), you can use OpenAI and a simple vector search. Because you only have 15+ projects, you don't even need a heavy Vector Database—you can just pass the metadata to the LLM to pick the right one.

Here is a conceptual Node.js backend endpoint that handles the user's request:

javascript
 Show full code block 
import express from 'express';
import { OpenAI } from 'openai';
import { getAllProjectsFromDB, getProjectJsonById } from './db.js';

const app = express();
const openai = new OpenAI({ apiKey: process.env.OPENAI_API_KEY });

app.post('/api/recommend-floorplan', async (req, res) => {
    const userPrompt = req.body.prompt; // e.g., "I want a 2 bedroom house"
    
    // 1. Get just the ID, Name, and Description of your 15+ projects
    const projects = await getAllProjectsFromDB(); 
    
    const systemPrompt = `
      You are an AI architect assistant. 
      Match the user's request to the best floor plan from our database.
      Here are the available floor plans:
      ${JSON.stringify(projects)}
      
      Respond ONLY with the exact ID of the best matching project.
    `;

    // 2. Ask OpenAI to pick the best project based on the user's prompt
    const completion = await openai.chat.completions.create({
        model: "gpt-4",
        messages: [
            { role: "system", content: systemPrompt },
            { role: "user", content: userPrompt }
        ]
    });

    const bestProjectId = completion.choices[0].message.content.trim();
    
    // 3. Fetch the heavy JSON layout for that specific project
    const projectData = await getProjectJsonById(bestProjectId);
    
    res.json({
        success: true,
        projectId: bestProjectId,
        projectData: projectData.json_data
    });
});
Step 3: Frontend Integration (Vue.js)
On your frontend, when the user selects a project or the RAG backend returns the recommended project, you simply pass the fetched JSON into your FloorPlanner engine.

Here is how you would write the Vue component logic to load the design:

javascript
 Show full code block 
<template>
  <div class="planner-container">
    <div id="planner-canvas"></div>
    
    <!-- AI Chat/Search Interface -->
    <div class="ai-assistant">
      <input v-model="userQuery" placeholder="E.g. I want a 2BHK..." />
      <button @click="askAIToFindLayout">Find Layout</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</template>

<script setup>
import { ref, onMounted } from 'vue';
import { FloorPlanner } from '@/core/engine2d/index.js'; // Adjust path

const userQuery = ref('');
let planner = null;

onMounted(() => {
    // Initialize your canvas engine
    const container = document.getElementById('planner-canvas');
    planner = new FloorPlanner(container);
});

// The RAG integration
async function askAIToFindLayout() {
    try {
        // 1. Call your RAG backend
        const response = await fetch('/api/recommend-floorplan', {
            method: 'POST',
            headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
            body: JSON.stringify({ prompt: userQuery.value })
        });
        
        const data = await response.json();
        
        if (data.success && data.projectData) {
            // 2. Load the JSON into your engine!
            // FloorPlanner.importState will parse the JSON and reconstruct all the walls
            planner.importState(data.projectData);
            
            // Note: Since importState already calls this.syncAll(), the canvas will 
            // automatically render the new walls. The user can instantly start dragging 
            // the anchors to change the walls while keeping your base design!
            
            alert('Loaded recommended floor plan!');
        }
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Failed to load layout from AI:', error);
    }
}
</script>
Why this works perfectly with your code:
If you look at your importState(jsonStr) implementation in src/core/engine2d/index.js:

It calls this.clearAll() to wipe the current canvas.
It parses the JSON and creates new PremiumWall, PremiumWidget, PremiumFurniture, etc.
It sets up the startAnchor and endAnchor for every wall.
It calls this.syncAll() to draw everything.
Because your engine reconstructs standard Anchor and PremiumWall objects, the moment the JSON is loaded, the user can click the "Select" tool (this.tool = 'select'), grab an anchor, and drag it. The walls will adjust exactly as if the user had drawn them from scratch!